1034
01:03:37,656 --> 01:03:39,801
<i>But instead of having long hair,
I gave them short hair.</i>

1035
01:03:39,825 --> 01:03:42,661
<i>Instead of making them tall,
I made them short.</i>

1036
01:03:48,209 --> 01:03:52,380
<i>So we had a lot of little people
that we put in costumes.</i>

1037
01:03:52,463 --> 01:03:55,424
<i>Again, technology is limited
in what we can do</i>

1038
01:03:55,508 --> 01:03:58,469
<i>to create these kind of creatures
and make them real.</i>

1039
01:03:58,552 --> 01:04:03,224
<i>Mostly it depends on the personality
of the actor inside the suit.</i>

1040
01:04:03,307 --> 01:04:06,310
<i>And I was fortunate
to find this one Ewok,</i>

1041
01:04:06,394 --> 01:04:09,021
<i>this little boy, Warwick Davis,</i>

1042
01:04:09,105 --> 01:04:13,442
<i>who was so expressive in his suit
and had such personality-</i>

1043
01:04:13,526 --> 01:04:16,320
<i>the way he walked
and the way he carried himself,</i>

1044
01:04:16,404 --> 01:04:17,905
<i>the way he was able to act-</i>

1045
01:04:17,988 --> 01:04:21,992
<i>he really was a hundred percent
into the character.</i>

1046
01:04:38,843 --> 01:04:42,638
<i>Again, the challenge of creating
a likable character...</i>

1047
01:04:42,721 --> 01:04:44,432
<i>out of a kid in a bear suit</i>

1048
01:04:44,515 --> 01:04:46,767
<i>that actually has a personality
as a character-</i>

1049
01:04:46,851 --> 01:04:50,855
<i>isn't just somebody who's there-
is very difficult.</i>

1050
01:04:50,938 --> 01:04:53,399
<i>You're always pushed to
how far can you go...</i>

1051
01:04:53,482 --> 01:04:58,154
<i>in having strange creatures,
exotic creatures...</i>

1052
01:04:58,237 --> 01:05:00,614
<i>who are actual characters
in the movie...</i>

1053
01:05:00,698 --> 01:05:04,535
<i>using this kind of,
you know, "real" technology-</i>

1054
01:05:04,618 --> 01:05:06,745
<i>a real puppet
or a real person in a suit.</i>

1055
01:05:06,829 --> 01:05:10,416
<i>Which was about all we had
in those days. It was very limiting.</i>

1056
01:05:13,169 --> 01:05:15,713
FISHER: <i>After a while,
it was very difficult for me</i>

1057
01:05:15,796 --> 01:05:17,840
<i>to do action sequences...</i>

1058
01:05:17,965 --> 01:05:20,217
<i>where I punched people
and hit people.</i>

1059
01:05:20,301 --> 01:05:22,928
<i>It's not really my thing.
It's stressful.</i>

1060
01:05:23,012 --> 01:05:27,057
<i>You pretend that you're shooting
at people and shooting guns...</i>

1061
01:05:27,141 --> 01:05:31,520
<i>and you're upset,
and you're crazed all morning long.</i>

1062
01:05:31,604 --> 01:05:37,026
<i>And so I'm revving up this thing
that is not innate in me necessarily.</i>

1063
01:05:37,151 --> 01:05:41,322
<i>And I can be
a pretty intense... broad.</i>

1064
01:05:41,405 --> 01:05:46,034
<i>But, you know, after a certain
amount of time, I was... done.</i>

1065
01:05:46,117 --> 01:05:49,370
<i>And you can't be done.
You have to keep going.</i>

1066
01:05:59,380 --> 01:06:03,134
LUCAS: <i>Warwick was so good in this
that I had been thinking about doing...</i>

1067
01:06:03,218 --> 01:06:07,222
<i>another kind of more traditional
fantasy that involved little people</i>

1068
01:06:07,305 --> 01:06:08,932
<i>and got him to star in that.</i>

1069
01:06:09,015 --> 01:06:10,683
<i>He's done a lot of roles since.</i>

1070
01:06:10,767 --> 01:06:13,186
<i>But that film was</i> Willow,
<i>directed by Ron Howard.</i>

1071
01:06:21,694 --> 01:06:24,280
<i>Now, as we get into
the last reels here of the film...</i>

1072
01:06:24,364 --> 01:06:28,159
<i>we're into the pulling
the plot together,</i>

1073
01:06:28,243 --> 01:06:32,330
<i>which ultimately is the trap
that the rebels are falling into.</i>

1074
01:06:32,413 --> 01:06:34,290
<i>The trap that Luke is falling into.</i>

1075
01:06:34,374 --> 01:06:37,585
<i>The trap that the emperor
has been planning to do away</i>

1076
01:06:37,669 --> 01:06:39,796
<i>with all his enemies.</i>

1077
01:06:39,879 --> 01:06:42,882
<i>So now this takes all of the dominoes
that have been set up...</i>

1078
01:06:42,966 --> 01:06:45,927
<i>in</i> A New Hope
<i>and</i> Empire Strikes Back

1079
01:06:46,010 --> 01:06:47,929
<i>and the first part of this film...</i>

1080
01:06:48,012 --> 01:06:51,099
<i>and starts to tip them over,
which in this particular case...</i>

1081
01:06:51,182 --> 01:06:52,701
<i>is reasonably complicated
'cause we have</i>

1082
01:06:52,725 --> 01:06:55,144
<i>three different stories going on-</i>

1083
01:06:55,228 --> 01:06:57,230
<i>One is in outer space with Lando</i>

1084
01:06:57,313 --> 01:06:59,566
<i>and the spaceships trying
to get into the Death Star.</i>

1085
01:06:59,649 --> 01:07:02,986
<i>One is on the planet
with Han Solo and Princess Leia...</i>

1086
01:07:03,069 --> 01:07:06,990
<i>trying to destroy the force field
that protects the Death Star.</i>

1087
01:07:07,073 --> 01:07:10,660
<i>And then you have Luke Skywalker
on the Death Star...</i>

1088
01:07:10,785 --> 01:07:15,540
<i>confronting his father and
the evil head of the Galactic Empire.</i>

1089
01:07:21,754 --> 01:07:25,383
<i>I do like to tell
a lot of different stories</i>

1090
01:07:25,466 --> 01:07:26,801
<i>and cut back and forth.</i>

1091
01:07:26,884 --> 01:07:29,929
<i>I'm not a big linear storyteller.</i>

1092
01:07:30,013 --> 01:07:33,182
American Graffiti, <i>there were four
stories being told simultaneously.</i>

1093
01:07:33,266 --> 01:07:35,310
<i>They were all going very fast.</i>

1094
01:07:35,393 --> 01:07:38,271
<i>I like simultaneity
and jumping back and forth.</i>

1095
01:07:38,354 --> 01:07:42,025
<i>That's what I'm most comfortable with,
for whatever reason.</i>

1096
01:07:42,108 --> 01:07:44,402
<i>Well, my first film,</i> THX,
<i>wasn't like that.</i>

1097
01:07:44,485 --> 01:07:47,085
<i>It was completely linear-
didn't cut back and forth with anything.</i>

1098
01:07:48,448 --> 01:07:50,825
<i>But after that I changed my mind.</i>
[CHUCKLES]

1099
01:07:55,955 --> 01:07:58,583
BURTT: <i>The hardest thing to create
in these films for me...</i>

1100
01:07:58,666 --> 01:08:01,210
<i>is always the voices.</i>

1101
01:08:01,294 --> 01:08:04,714
<i>Sound effects is one issue.
But voices are listened to...</i>

1102
01:08:04,797 --> 01:08:07,341
<i>with a very critical ear
by the audience.</i>

1103
01:08:07,424 --> 01:08:10,093
<i>We're all experts at
identifying voices</i>

1104
01:08:10,177 --> 01:08:12,554
<i>and understanding
where they come from...</i>

1105
01:08:12,638 --> 01:08:16,141
<i>and read into all
the nuances of voice quality,</i>

1106
01:08:16,224 --> 01:08:18,393
<i>intonation and performance.</i>

1107
01:08:18,477 --> 01:08:21,772
<i>The biggest voice task in</i> Jedi
<i>was the development...</i>

1108
01:08:21,855 --> 01:08:25,776
<i>of the Ewok languages
and the Ewok character voices.</i>

1109
01:08:25,859 --> 01:08:28,737
<i>The first step was to create a language.</i>

1110
01:08:28,820 --> 01:08:31,323
<i>Now, I don't create a language really
by sitting down...</i>

1111
01:08:31,406 --> 01:08:35,744
<i>and trying to reason it out
as to what the cultural context is...</i>

1112
01:08:35,827 --> 01:08:38,580
<i>and how I'm gonna conjugate verbs
or any of that.</i>

1113
01:08:38,664 --> 01:08:40,957
<i>Generally speaking, we've worked...</i>

1114
01:08:41,041 --> 01:08:44,753
<i>by first listening
to actual voice recordings...</i>

1115
01:08:44,836 --> 01:08:47,214
<i>from around the world
of different languages...</i>

1116
01:08:47,297 --> 01:08:50,676
<i>until we find a language
which sounds exotic, not familiar,</i>

1117
01:08:50,759 --> 01:08:54,388
<i>and has something of
the character of the types of aliens</i>

1118
01:08:54,471 --> 01:08:56,098
<i>we're trying to create.</i>

1119
01:08:56,181 --> 01:08:57,659
<i>Even though
we don't speak that language,</i>

1120
01:08:57,683 --> 01:08:59,434
<i>we'll listen to recordings of it...</i>

1121
01:08:59,518 --> 01:09:02,854
<i>and we'll begin to extract sounds
from that language...</i>

1122
01:09:02,938 --> 01:09:06,733
<i>and eventually build up
kind of a double-talk set of sounds...</i>

1123
01:09:06,858 --> 01:09:09,986
<i>in which we're mimicking
this exotic language.</i>

1124
01:09:10,070 --> 01:09:15,242
<i>The Ewok language
is really derivative of Kalmyk,</i>

1125
01:09:15,367 --> 01:09:18,995
<i>which is a language
that comes out of Asia...</i>

1126
01:09:19,079 --> 01:09:21,790
<i>in areas of central China.</i>

1127
01:09:21,873 --> 01:09:24,710
<i>I saw a documentary on television...</i>

1128
01:09:24,793 --> 01:09:27,796
<i>that interviewed some people
in this region of China-</i>

1129
01:09:27,879 --> 01:09:29,881
<i>some nomadic tribesmen-</i>

1130
01:09:29,965 --> 01:09:33,135
<i>"and I thought," Wow.
This language is very interesting.</i>

1131
01:09:33,218 --> 01:09:36,304
<i>"It has something
we haven't heard before.</i>

1132
01:09:36,430 --> 01:09:39,891
<i>It seems like it would be
something good for the Ewoks."</i>

1133
01:09:44,980 --> 01:09:46,857
<i>We began to look around to see</i>

1134
01:09:46,940 --> 01:09:49,192
<i>if we could find anyone
that spoke this language.</i>

1135
01:09:49,276 --> 01:09:52,362
<i>Of course, there wasn't offhand
anybody immediately available...</i>

1136
01:09:52,446 --> 01:09:56,491
<i>since it came from
a remote part of the world.</i>

1137
01:09:56,575 --> 01:10:00,036
<i>But we finally, through some research,
came into contact with some refugees...</i>

1138
01:10:00,120 --> 01:10:02,456
<i>who had come from that part of China.</i>

1139
01:10:02,539 --> 01:10:04,791
<i>And in particular, an elderly woman-</i>

1140
01:10:04,916 --> 01:10:07,961
<i>she was probably in her 80s-
was brought to us.</i>

1141
01:10:08,086 --> 01:10:10,464
<i>She didn't speak any English.</i>

1142
01:10:10,547 --> 01:10:15,552
<i>She had recently immigrated
from primitive regions of China.</i>

1143
01:10:15,635 --> 01:10:18,346
<i>She had lived in a tribe...</i>

1144
01:10:18,430 --> 01:10:23,477
<i>as some kind of a quasi-nomadic
existence all her life.</i>

1145
01:10:23,560 --> 01:10:25,312
<i>She probably didn't really understand</i>

1146
01:10:25,395 --> 01:10:28,732
<i>what we were trying to do
in recording her voice for a movie.</i>

1147
01:10:28,815 --> 01:10:31,150
<i>But we approach these things...</i>

1148
01:10:31,233 --> 01:10:33,819
<i>by usually bringing the person
into the studio...</i>

1149
01:10:33,903 --> 01:10:35,905
<i>and I sit down with them.</i>

1150
01:10:35,988 --> 01:10:38,574
<i>You get her to tell stories.</i>

1151
01:10:38,657 --> 01:10:42,119
<i>This is usually how I do it.
A person who's not an actor...</i>

1152
01:10:42,244 --> 01:10:46,040
<i>you just don't put a microphone
in front of them and say, "Okay, talk."</i>

1153
01:10:46,123 --> 01:10:49,335
<i>You usually wanna put them at ease
and give them something to do.</i>

1154
01:10:49,418 --> 01:10:53,839
<i>What I found with her and what
I've done with other native people...</i>

1155
01:10:53,923 --> 01:10:57,593
<i>was to sit down with them
and have them tell me folk tales...</i>

1156
01:10:57,676 --> 01:11:00,554
<i>and to pretend
they were telling me stories,</i>

1157
01:11:00,638 --> 01:11:03,724
<i>bedtime stories, as if I was a child.</i>

1158
01:11:03,808 --> 01:11:06,310
<i>They can tell me a story
in which they may do</i>

1159
01:11:06,393 --> 01:11:08,896
<i>the voices of different characters...</i>

1160
01:11:08,979 --> 01:11:12,691
<i>and they can inject a sense of drama
into what they're saying.</i>

1161
01:11:20,950 --> 01:11:24,620
<i>She wanted a bottle of vodka
and, uh, we provided that for her.</i>

1162
01:11:24,703 --> 01:11:29,041
<i>And she got very lucid and gave us
some wonderful sounds.</i>

1163
01:11:29,124 --> 01:11:31,961
<i>We referred to this woman
as "Grandma Vodka"...</i>

1164
01:11:32,044 --> 01:11:34,713
<i>because we couldn't pronounce
her real name.</i>

1165
01:11:34,797 --> 01:11:37,842
<i>And a session in the studio with her...</i>

1166
01:11:37,925 --> 01:11:41,220
<i>gave us not only the inspiration
but gave us the basis...</i>

1167
01:11:41,303 --> 01:11:43,639
<i>for a lot of the Ewok voices.</i>

1168
01:11:43,722 --> 01:11:47,977
<i>We were able to take recordings
that she gave us...</i>

1169
01:11:48,060 --> 01:11:50,938
<i>of her laughing,
of her telling stories,</i>

1170
01:11:51,021 --> 01:11:55,734
<i>of her doing
little character voices high and low...</i>

1171
01:11:55,818 --> 01:11:58,988
<i>and out of that
came a range of sounds,</i>

1172
01:11:59,071 --> 01:12:01,574
<i>both male and female voices,</i>

1173
01:12:02,032 --> 01:12:04,869
<i>which provided the basis
for the Ewok language.</i>

1174
01:12:13,085 --> 01:12:16,797
<i>Once we got comfortable
with orchestrating those sounds...</i>

1175
01:12:16,881 --> 01:12:18,316
<i>and picking out the things we liked,</i>

1176
01:12:18,340 --> 01:12:20,718
<i>then we brought
in our own staff of actors-</i>

1177
01:12:20,801 --> 01:12:22,928
<i>usually people on our own crew.</i>

1178
01:12:23,012 --> 01:12:25,639
<i>Also, people in the Bay Area
that we knew...</i>

1179
01:12:25,723 --> 01:12:29,018
<i>who had interesting quality
to their voices.</i>

1180
01:12:29,101 --> 01:12:33,689
<i>They either had a high-pitched voice
or they had a very raspy kind of voice.</i>

1181
01:12:33,772 --> 01:12:38,027
<i>And we brought them in,
played these recordings of Kalmyk...</i>

1182
01:12:38,110 --> 01:12:39,820
<i>and had them imitate it.</i>

1183
01:12:39,904 --> 01:12:44,033
<i>And we wrote out phonetically
things for people to say.</i>

1184
01:12:44,116 --> 01:12:48,913
<i>We assigned particular voices
we liked to certain Ewok characters...</i>

1185
01:12:48,996 --> 01:12:52,875
<i>like Wicket
or the chief of the village...</i>

1186
01:12:52,958 --> 01:12:55,001
<i>or the witch doctor of the village.</i>

1187
01:12:55,084 --> 01:12:59,505
<i>And then the crowd sounds
of the Ewoks were our crew members...</i>

1188
01:12:59,589 --> 01:13:03,885
<i>imitating what they had heard
in these exotic languages.</i>

1189
01:13:03,968 --> 01:13:06,012
<i>And it was just all put together...</i>

1190
01:13:06,095 --> 01:13:08,932
<i>in kind of a collage that unto itself,</i>

1191
01:13:09,015 --> 01:13:11,476
<i>I guess, ended up having
a consistent sound to it.</i>

1192
01:13:21,653 --> 01:13:25,531
<i>One of the favourite recordings we got
from this elderly Chinese woman...</i>

1193
01:13:25,615 --> 01:13:27,742
<i>was a little song that she sang</i>

1194
01:13:27,825 --> 01:13:30,036
<i>which you'll hear several times
in the Ewok village...</i>

1195
01:13:30,119 --> 01:13:33,414
